<div class="wrapper">

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">What is Freestyle Footbag?</h2>
    <p>
      Freestyle footbag is the only footbag discipline that allows use of the entire body: head,
      shoulders, chest, and arms are all in play alongside the feet. Unlike net footbag, which is
      scored on rallies and placement, freestyle rewards trick difficulty, add count, variety, and
      individual style.
    </p>
    <p>
      Tricks are built on a set notation system: each trick is defined by a set (the arc of the bag),
      a body action (dexterity, spin, or combination), and the adds: additional difficulty layers
      stacked before the catch. Higher add counts indicate greater difficulty.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Competition Formats</h2>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Routines</h3>
    <p>
      The primary competition format. Competitors perform a timed routine to music of their
      choice, with time limits set by the event format. Judges score on four axes: difficulty
      (add count and trick complexity), composition (the variety and breadth of distinct
      moves performed across the routine), execution (clean contacts and controlled catches),
      and presentation (musicality, flow, and style). Routines may be performed solo or in
      pairs.
    </p>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">30 Second Shred</h3>
    <p>
      A focused burst format. Competitors have 30 seconds to perform as many high-difficulty
      tricks as possible. Scoring emphasises raw trick output and adds per trick rather than
      presentation or flow. A high-intensity showcase of technical ability.
    </p>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Sick 3</h3>
    <p>
      Competitors nominate three specific tricks in advance and attempt to land each cleanly.
      The format tests precise execution of self-declared difficulty: there is no room to
      substitute easier tricks if a trick fails. Judges score on successful completion, add count,
      and execution quality.
    </p>

    <h3 class="content-subheading">Circle Contest</h3>
    <p>
      Players compete in small shared circles of three or four, taking turns to perform runs
      of linked tricks. A round may run in one or two phases with different judging emphases:
      a variety phase, where judges compare the breadth of distinct moves each player shows,
      and a density phase, where they compare the sustained link difficulty across each run.
      Part jam and part contest, it is the most social of the judged formats.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Trick Records</h2>
    <p>
      Outside formal competition, the freestyle community tracks per-trick consecutive records,
      documented attempts where a player completes a given trick many times in a row
      without a miss. Records are sourced from video evidence; they are well documented
      but most have not been independently cross-checked.
    </p>
    <a href="/freestyle/records" class="btn btn-outline">Browse Trick Records</a>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Move Sets Reference</h2>
    <p>
      New-school freestyle is built on a shared set notation system. Each set name describes the
      bag's arc, the plant foot, and the direction of the dexterity. Understanding set notation
      unlocks the naming logic behind nearly every trick name in the records.
    </p>
    <a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=sets" class="btn btn-outline">View Set Hub</a>
  </section>

